Reference-contexts: The purpose of a database design model is to offer constructs for the efficient storage, retrieval and manipulation of data. In database design, it is customary to organize data information using a three-step process <ref> [Elmasri and Navathe, 1989] </ref>. The first step is a concise description of the users' needs expressed using "diagram tools" like a box and arrow or some other simple visual paradigm. The idea is to identify key invariants or links within the data application as well as the relationships between them.
